f(x) = -\dfrac{1}{(2+x)^2}
f(x) = \sum\limits_{n=0}^\infty \dfrac{f'^{(n)}(0)}{n!}x^n \\ f^{(n)}(0) = -\frac14, \frac{2*1}8, -\frac{3*2*1}{16}, ... \textrm{ for } n = 0, 1, 2, ... \\  f(x) = \sum\limits_{n=0}^\infty \dfrac{(-1)^{n+1}(n+1)!}{2^{n+2}}\dfrac{x^n}{n!} = \sum\limits_{n=0}^\infty \dfrac{(-1)^{n+1}(n+1)}{4 (2^n)}x^n
\lim_{n \to \infty} | \dfrac{(-1)^{n+2}(n+2)x^{n+1}}{4(2^{n+1})}\dfrac{4(2^n)}{(-1)^{n+1}(n+1)x^n} | = \\ |\dfrac{x}{2}| \lim_{n \to \infty} | \dfrac{(n+2)}{(n+1)}| = |\dfrac{x}{2}| < 1 \\  \therefore |x| < 2
\dfrac{d}{dx}\dfrac{1}{2+x} = f(x)
\dfrac{1}{2+x}
z=-x/2
\frac1{1-z}=1+z+z^2+z^3+\ldots
\frac1{2+x}=\frac12\frac1{1-\left(-\frac{x}2\right)}=\frac12\sum_{n\ge 0}\left(-\frac{x}2\right)^n=\frac12\sum_{n\ge 0}\frac{(-1)^n}{2^n}x^n
